<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Erotylidae" genus="Episcapha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Episcapha (Ephicaspa) quadriconcava" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadriconcava" subGenus="Ephicaspa">Episcapha (Ephicaspa) quadriconcava</taxonomicName>
is closest to 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Erotylidae" genus="Episcapha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Episcapha (Ephicaspa) yunnanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis" subGenus="Ephicaspa">Episcapha (Ephicaspa) yunnanensis</taxonomicName>
Li &amp; Ren, 2006, due to the similar form and color of the body in both species. The new species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Erotylidae" genus="Episcapha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Episcapha (Ephicaspa) yunnanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis" subGenus="Ephicaspa">Episcapha (Ephicaspa) yunnanensis</taxonomicName>
by the head without ocular lines, pronotum widest at middle, mesoventrite with a median quadrate depression, aedeagus with median lobe narrowing to a point in lateral view. 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Erotylidae" genus="Episcapha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Episcapha (Ephicaspa) yunnanensis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis" subGenus="Ephicaspa">Episcapha (Ephicaspa) yunnanensis</taxonomicName>
with ocular lines on head, pronotum widest at 
<pageBreakToken pageId="4" pageNumber="51" start="start">base</pageBreakToken>
, mesoventrite with a median trapezoidal depression, aedeagus with median lobe hooked at apex in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
